title: For Sale:  M1 Garand Springfield Mfg.  WWII Receiver Mfg. 1943Lock Bar Sights C&R NR
postcontent: This Military Rifle is a M1 Garand mfg. by the Springfield Armory in 9/43. It saw service in WWII and then later went through an Arsenal Re-Build and was re-barreled in 10/46. The barrel is marked (SA 10-46) All of the internal parts are that I can see are USGI and the mechanics worked fine during test firing. The ME measures "3" and the TE measures "4" which is well within good shooting standards. The wood has numerous marks from military service, but no major issues such as chips, splits or cracks. There is a "rack number" on the bottom of the butt stock which is conducive of rifles that were issued to the Dane's after WWII. This Rifle also has retained the early "Lock Bar Sights" that are quite rare to see on M1 Garands these days. It also has the "Milled Trigger Guard" which is conducive of early Rifles.

title: For Sale/Trade:  FEG PA-63 pistol in 9x18 Makarov  + AMMO
postcontent:
For Sale: 1 PA-63 pistol made by FEG.  7+1 capacity, 3.9" barrel, chambered in 9x18 Makarov, and imported by CIA.  This is a small, lightweight, and easily concealable Hungarian made military/police clone of the Walther PP/PPK line of pistols.
The simple blowback design and fixed barrel make it pretty accurate, and it fires a cartridge that is cheaper than .380acp and power-wise between .380acp and 9x19 Luger. 

It comes with 3 magazines, 229 rounds of ammo (178 Brass cased Fiocci, and the rest is steel cased Silver bear, all FMJ) and 2 basic BLACKHAWK! holsters.  One holster is IWB the other is an OWB belt holster. I'll also include an extra Wolf heavy recoil spring and couple of other small replacement parts.

It is super easy to take down and clean, and a very simple design. It has a combo safety/decocker.  There is some bluing wear on the muzzle, and some of the machining on the internals is a little rough, but the gun functions flawlessly, and is in good condition overall, especially for a 40ish year old milsurp.  The double action trigger pull is smooth and not unreasonably long and the break of the single action pull is excellent.  Recoil is snappy due to the light weight, but manageable.  I've put about 300 rounds through it, and carried it some, and it is an excellent inexpensive carry or backup pistol.  I much prefer this over a Kel Tec or something similar.

Just to clarify for people not as familiar with this  caliber; while this gun is technically a 9mm, 9x18 Makarov and 9x19 Luger are two separate calibers that are not interchangeable.  While it is unlikely you'd find Mak ammo at the local Walmart, it is pretty common at gun shops across the state, and can be found easily online, with the cheap steel cased stuff being comparable to cheaper 9mm Luger in price at about $15 for a 50 box before shipping if you shop around (current 3/6/14 price,) and slightly less if you buy in bulk.

Serious inquiries only.  Firm on price, lowballers ignored.  I'd be happy to answer questions only if they haven't been covered here already, and can provide additional pictures to a potential buyer.  Face to face cash transaction with a Vermont ID. Must be legally able to own a firearm and be willing to sign bill of sale.
